'''The Land is Ours''' is a British [[land rights]] campaign advocating access to the land, its resources, and the planning processes set up in 1995 by [[George Monbiot]] and others.<ref>{{Citation|last=Monbiot |first=George |author-link= |publication-date= |date=22 February 1995 |year= |title=A Land Reform Manifesto |periodical=The Guardian |publication-place=London |place= |url=http://www.monbiot.com/archives/1995/02/22/a-land-reform-manifesto/#more-625 |issn= |doi= |oclc= |accessdate=2008-08-06 |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3AMonbiot+intitle%3AA+Land+Reform+Manifesto&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517032438/http://www.monbiot.com/archives/1995/02/22/a-land-reform-manifesto/ |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref>

Their first campaign was the occupation of the disused [[Wisley Airfield]] in [[Surrey]] by 400 people in 1995, from which there was a live broadcast on the BBC's ''[[Newsnight]]'' programme. Nearby [[St. George's Hill]] is symbolically significant as the site of a 1649 protest, when the [[Diggers]] planted vegetables on the [[common land]] there. 

Throughout the summer of 1996, the group set up Pure Genius!!, an [[eco-village]] on a derelict former distillery site owned by [[Guinness]] in [[Wandsworth]], [[London]]. The [[Squatting|squatted]] community was evicted the day before the [[London Wildlife Trust]] were meeting to officially designate it as a conservation site containing many species of flowers and birds classed as extremely rare in London.{{cn|date=October 2018}}

On 1 April 1999, on the 350th anniversary of [[Gerrard Winstanley]] and the Diggers' occupation of the same hill, The Land Is Ours organised a rally, then occupied land at St. Georges Hill near Weybridge, Surrey.{{cn|date=October 2018}}

In April 2004, The Land Is Ours occupied [[Castell Henllys]], a tourist site with reconstructed [[Iron Age]] [[roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouses]], in protest at [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]]'s decision to demolish [[That Roundhouse]] at nearby [[Brithdir Mawr]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}

In 2009, a group inspired by The Land Is Ours opened [[Kew Bridge Eco Village]], a squat on land owned by property developers [[Berkeley Group Holdings|St George]]; this was evicted on 27 May 2010.{{cn|date=October 2018}}

